  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation replaces a
select guarded by an fcmp (<= 0.0) between -x and x with a call to llvm.fabs. For
NaN inputs, the original code returns the input x (here a signaling NaN with a
specific sign bit), while fabs(x) canonicalizes and clears the sign bit, changing
the value. This violates semantics unless we can prove that NaNs cannot
occur.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first transformation is in
InstCombineSelect::visitSelectInst via foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs. The log shows it
directly folds the select to a fabs intrinsic. Alive2 counterexample uses %x =
SNaN (#xfd00). Source select: fcmp ole %x, 0.0 is false for NaN, so it chooses %x
(SNaN, sign preserved). Target fabs(x) produces NaN with positive sign (#x7d00),
causing mismatch.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs (lines
~2768-2893), there are two sub-patterns:\n- The first pattern matches TrueVal as
fsub +0.0, X and predicates OLE/UGT and directly emits fabs without any fast-math
flags gate regarding NaNs.\n- The second pattern handling fneg requires
hasNoSignedZeros and hasNoNaNs before folding (and includes FMF propagation). The
bug is that the fsub(+0.0, X) path does not require no-NaNs, so it allows folding
even when NaNs are possible, changing NaN sign behavior and quieting
behavior.\nThus, the transformation is unsound without the nnan (no-NaNs)
assumption.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nEdit at lines 2796-2804 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp to gate the fsub(+0.0, X)
-> fabs(X) fold behind a no-NaNs check similar to the fneg path. Specifically,
before creating fabs in both the non-swap (OLE/ULE) and swap (OGT/UGT) cases,
ensure SI.hasNoNaNs() (or equivalently, require no-NaNs from the condition's FMF
propagated or present on the select). Minimal safe fix:\n- Insert a check: if
(!SI.hasNoNaNs()) continue; right after confirming TrueVal is fsub(+0.0, X) and
before applying either fold. Alternatively, wrap each branch with this condition.
This ensures the fold only occurs when NaNs cannot appear, preserving NaN
sign-bit behavior equivalence.\n\nSuggested patch conceptually:\n  if
(match(TrueVal, m_FSub(m_PosZeroFP(), m_Specific(X)))) {\n    if
(!SI.hasNoNaNs())\n      continue;\n    if (!Swap && (Pred == FCmpInst::FCMP_OLE
|| Pred == FCmpInst::FCMP_ULE)) {\n      ... create fabs ...\n    }\n    if (Swap
&& (Pred == FCmpInst::FCMP_OGT || Pred == FCmpInst::FCMP_UGT)) {\n      ...
create fabs ...\n    }\n  }\n\nThis aligns the fsub path's requirements with the
later fneg path, which already mandates hasNoNaNs and hasNoSignedZeros, avoiding
incorrect NaN handling.\n\nNOTICE: Assertions:\nNo assertions are being altered;
we add a guard to prevent the transformation when preconditions (no-NaNs) are not
met.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy gating the fsub(+0.0, X) -> fabs(X) fold on hasNoNaNs,
we avoid changing NaN sign behavior and quieting in cases where NaNs may occur,
fixing the incorrect transformation shown by Alive2. The fold remains valid when
nnan is guaranteed, maintaining optimization opportunities without violating
semantics.",
